units:
# ============================================================================
# FEATURE: imp v0.1 — First usable release
# ============================================================================
- id: '1'
  title: "imp v0.1 — First usable release"
  status: open
  priority: 0
  feature: true
  description: |
    Get imp to the point where it can have real multi-turn conversations with
    tool use, across providers, with a clean TUI. Validated by Mario's pi blog
    post: a minimal agent with core tools, <1K token system prompt, YOLO mode,
    and full observability is competitive with the best coding agents.

    Done when:
    - imp starts, connects to Anthropic, has a conversation with tool use
    - All tools work (no "not yet implemented" stubs remaining)
    - Unit tests exist for critical paths (tools, providers, agent loop, session)
    - Can switch providers mid-session (Anthropic → OpenAI → Google)
    - System prompt + tool definitions < 1K tokens (baseline, before AGENTS.md)
    - Headless and RPC modes work for orchestration

# ============================================================================
# PHASE 1: Stub tool implementations (parallelizable, no deps on each other)
# ============================================================================

- id: '1.1'
  title: "Implement find tool"
  status: open
  priority: 0
  parent: '1'
  produces:
    - find-tool
  has_verify: true
  verify: "cd /Users/asher/imp && cargo test --lib tools::find -- --nocapture 2>&1 | grep -q 'test result: ok' && ! grep -q 'not yet implemented' crates/imp-core/src/tools/find.rs"
  description: |
    ## Task
    Implement the `find` tool — search for files by glob pattern, respecting .gitignore.

    ## Steps
    1. Open `crates/imp-core/src/tools/find.rs`
    2. Replace the stub `execute` with real implementation:
       - Extract `pattern` (required), `path` (optional, defaults to cwd), `limit` (optional, default 1000)
       - Use `walkdir` crate to walk the directory tree
       - Match files against the glob pattern using the `glob` or `globset` crate (check what's available or use basic matching)
       - Respect `.gitignore` by checking `ignore` crate or manually skipping `.git/`, `node_modules/`, `target/`, etc.
       - Apply limit, sort results alphabetically
       - Apply output truncation (1000 results max, 50KB max)
       - Return matched paths relative to the search directory
    3. Add unit tests in the same file (test with a temp directory)

    ## Context
    ```rust
    // from crates/imp-core/src/tools/mod.rs
    pub struct ToolOutput {
        pub content: Vec<imp_llm::ContentBlock>,
        pub details: serde_json::Value,
        pub is_error: bool,
    }
    impl ToolOutput {
        pub fn text(text: impl Into<String>) -> Self { ... }
        pub fn error(msg: impl Into<String>) -> Self { ... }
    }
    pub struct ToolContext {
        pub cwd: PathBuf,
        pub signal: tokio_util::sync::CancellationToken,
    }
    ```

    ## Files
    - crates/imp-core/src/tools/find.rs (modify — full implementation)
    - crates/imp-core/src/tools/mod.rs (read — ToolOutput, ToolContext types)
    - crates/imp-core/src/tools/grep.rs (read — reference implementation for similar tool)
    - crates/imp-core/Cargo.toml (modify — add `globset` dep if needed)

    ## Don't
    - Don't shell out to `fd` — implement natively with walkdir
    - Don't change the Tool trait or ToolOutput types

- id: '1.2'
  title: "Implement ls tool"
  status: open
  priority: 0
  parent: '1'
  produces:
    - ls-tool
  has_verify: true
  verify: "cd /Users/asher/imp && cargo test --lib tools::ls -- --nocapture 2>&1 | grep -q 'test result: ok' && ! grep -q 'not yet implemented' crates/imp-core/src/tools/ls.rs"
  description: |
    ## Task
    Implement the `ls` tool — list directory contents with '/' suffix for directories.

    ## Steps
    1. Open `crates/imp-core/src/tools/ls.rs`
    2. Replace the stub `execute` with real implementation:
       - Extract `path` (optional, defaults to cwd), `limit` (optional, default 500)
       - Read directory entries with `std::fs::read_dir`
       - Sort alphabetically, append '/' to directories
       - Include dotfiles
       - Apply limit and 50KB truncation
       - Return one entry per line
    3. Add unit tests (test with temp directory containing files and subdirectories)

    ## Context
    ```rust
    pub struct ToolContext {
        pub cwd: PathBuf,
        pub signal: tokio_util::sync::CancellationToken,
    }
    ```

    ## Files
    - crates/imp-core/src/tools/ls.rs (modify — full implementation)
    - crates/imp-core/src/tools/mod.rs (read — types)

    ## Don't
    - Don't shell out to `ls` or `eza`
    - Don't add recursive listing — this is a single-directory tool

- id: '1.3'
  title: "Implement shell tool loader"
  status: open
  priority: 1
  parent: '1'
  produces:
    - shell-tool-loader
  has_verify: true
  verify: "cd /Users/asher/imp && cargo test --lib tools::shell -- --nocapture 2>&1 | grep -q 'test result: ok' && ! grep -q 'TODO' crates/imp-core/src/tools/shell.rs"
  description: |
    ## Task
    Implement the shell tool loader — parse TOML tool definitions and register them as tools.

    ## Steps
    1. Open `crates/imp-core/src/tools/shell.rs`
    2. Implement `load_shell_tools(dir, registry)`:
       - Walk the directory for `*.toml` files
       - Parse each as `ShellToolDef` (types already defined in the file)
       - Create a `ShellTool` struct that implements the `Tool` trait
       - `execute` should:
         a. Validate params against the schema
         b. Interpolate `{param}` and `{param|default}` placeholders into args
         c. Run the command with `tokio::process::Command`
         d. Capture stdout/stderr, apply truncation
         e. Return as ToolOutput
       - If command binary not found, return helpful error with install_hint if available
       - Register each tool in the registry
    3. Add unit tests:
       - Create a temp dir with a test TOML tool definition
       - Load it, verify it registers
       - Execute it, verify interpolation works

    ## Context
    The TOML format is already defined:
    ```toml
    name = "my_tool"
    label = "My Tool"
    description = "Does something"
    readonly = true
    [params]
    url = { type = "string", description = "The URL" }
    [exec]
    command = "echo"
    args = ["{url}"]
    timeout = 30
    ```

    ## Files
    - crates/imp-core/src/tools/shell.rs (modify — full implementation)
    - crates/imp-core/src/tools/mod.rs (read — Tool trait, ToolRegistry)
    - crates/imp-core/src/tools/bash.rs (read — reference for command execution)

    ## Don't
    - Don't change ShellToolDef/ShellExecDef types (already correct)
    - Don't add new dependencies — use tokio::process::Command

# ============================================================================
# PHASE 2: Google provider (lower priority than tools)
# ============================================================================

- id: '1.4'
  title: "Implement Google Gemini provider"
  status: open
  priority: 1
  parent: '1'
  dependencies:
    - '1.7'
  produces:
    - google-provider
  has_verify: true
  verify: "cd /Users/asher/imp && cargo test --lib providers::google -- --nocapture 2>&1 | grep -q 'test result: ok' && ! grep -q 'TODO' crates/imp-llm/src/providers/google.rs"
  description: |
    ## Task
    Implement the Google Gemini API provider with SSE streaming, tool calling, and thinking support.

    ## Steps
    1. Open `crates/imp-llm/src/providers/google.rs` (currently a stub returning empty stream)
    2. Implement the full provider following the same pattern as `anthropic.rs`:
       a. Define Gemini wire-format types (request/response)
       b. Implement `build_request` to convert unified types to Gemini API format
       c. Implement `stream` with SSE parsing (Gemini uses `generateContent` with `streamGenerateContent`)
       d. Handle tool call accumulation (Google streams tool calls incrementally)
       e. Map thinking/reasoning (Gemini's `thinkingConfig` with `thinkingBudget`)
       f. Map stop reasons, usage tracking
    3. Add the full model registry (Gemini 2.5 Pro, 2.5 Flash, etc.)
    4. Add unit tests for request serialization and SSE event parsing

    ## API Reference
    - Endpoint: `https://generativelanguage.googleapis.com/v1beta/models/{model}:streamGenerateContent`
    - Auth: API key as query parameter `?key={api_key}`
    - Content format: `contents[].parts[].text`, `functionCall`, `functionResponse`
    - Thinking: `generationConfig.thinkingConfig.thinkingBudget`

    ## Context
    The Anthropic provider (1442 lines) is the reference implementation. Study:
    - How it builds requests from unified types
    - How it parses SSE events via state machine
    - How it accumulates tool call arguments from deltas
    - How it tracks usage

    ## Files
    - crates/imp-llm/src/providers/google.rs (modify — full implementation)
    - crates/imp-llm/src/providers/anthropic.rs (read — reference implementation)
    - crates/imp-llm/src/provider.rs (read — Provider trait)
    - crates/imp-llm/src/message.rs (read — unified message types)
    - crates/imp-llm/src/stream.rs (read — StreamEvent types)

    ## Don't
    - Don't change the Provider trait or unified message types
    - Don't add image support yet if it complicates things — text + tools first

    ## Quirks from pi blog
    - Google doesn't support tool call streaming (as of pi's blog post — verify if still true)
    - If still true, accumulate the full tool call response before emitting StreamEvent::ToolCall

# ============================================================================
# PHASE 3: Code intelligence (tree-sitter)
# ============================================================================

- id: '1.5'
  title: "Tree-sitter engine + probe_search, probe_extract, scan, ast_grep tools"
  status: open
  priority: 1
  parent: '1'
  produces:
    - tree-sitter-engine
    - tree-sitter-tools
  has_verify: true
  verify: "cd /Users/asher/imp && cargo test --lib tools::tree_sitter -- --nocapture 2>&1 | grep -q 'test result: ok' && ! grep -q 'not yet implemented' crates/imp-core/src/tools/tree_sitter.rs"
  description: |
    ## Task
    Add tree-sitter as a native dependency and implement the 4 code intelligence tools:
    probe_search, probe_extract, scan, ast_grep.

    ## Steps
    1. Add tree-sitter + language grammar crates to `crates/imp-core/Cargo.toml`:
       - `tree-sitter = "0.24"` (or latest)
       - Language grammars: `tree-sitter-rust`, `tree-sitter-typescript`, `tree-sitter-javascript`,
         `tree-sitter-python`, `tree-sitter-go`, `tree-sitter-c`, `tree-sitter-cpp`, `tree-sitter-java`,
         `tree-sitter-ruby`, `tree-sitter-bash`, `tree-sitter-json`, `tree-sitter-toml`,
         `tree-sitter-yaml`, `tree-sitter-html`, `tree-sitter-css`, `tree-sitter-markdown`
       - Also add `grep` crate (for in-process ripgrep in probe_search)
    2. Create a `TreeSitterEngine` struct with methods:
       - `parse(source, language) -> Tree`
       - `extract_block(tree, source, line) -> Option<CodeBlock>` — find enclosing function/class/struct
       - `extract_structure(tree, source) -> FileStructure` — all top-level symbols
       - `pattern_search(tree, source, pattern) -> Vec<Match>` — ast-grep style
       - `detect_language(path) -> Option<&str>` — from file extension
    3. Implement each tool in `crates/imp-core/src/tools/tree_sitter.rs`:
       - **probe_search**: Use `grep` crate for text matching, then tree-sitter to expand to complete blocks
       - **probe_extract**: Parse file, find block at line/symbol, return complete code block
       - **scan**: Parse file(s), extract top-level structure (functions, types, imports)
       - **ast_grep**: Parse file, match AST pattern, optionally apply replacement
    4. Add unit tests with small Rust/Python/TypeScript source snippets

    ## Files
    - crates/imp-core/Cargo.toml (modify — add tree-sitter deps)
    - crates/imp-core/src/tools/tree_sitter.rs (modify — full implementation, likely 500-800 lines)
    - crates/imp-core/src/tools/mod.rs (read — Tool trait)

    ## Don't
    - Don't try to support all 18 languages in v1 — start with Rust, TypeScript, Python, Go, C
    - Don't shell out to `probe` or `ast-grep` CLIs — this is native

# ============================================================================
# PHASE 4: Testing (parallelizable, critical for pi's lesson of "test early")
# ============================================================================

- id: '1.6'
  title: "imp-core tool unit tests"
  status: open
  priority: 0
  parent: '1'
  produces:
    - tool-tests
  has_verify: true
  verify: "cd /Users/asher/imp && cargo test --lib tools -- --nocapture 2>&1 | grep -q 'test result: ok'"
  description: |
    ## Task
    Write unit tests for all implemented tools: read, write, edit, multi_edit, bash, grep, diff_show, diff_apply.

    ## Steps
    For each tool, add a `#[cfg(test)] mod tests` block in the tool's file with tests:

    1. **read.rs**: Test reading a text file, reading with offset/limit, reading nonexistent file (error),
       reading an image file (returns image content block), large file truncation
    2. **write.rs**: Test writing new file, overwriting existing, creating parent directories,
       verify content matches after write
    3. **edit.rs**: Test exact match replace, multiple occurrences (should fail or replace first?),
       match not found (error), whitespace sensitivity
    4. **multi_edit.rs**: Test sequential edits, edit that depends on previous edit's result,
       atomic failure (if one edit fails, no edits applied)
    5. **bash.rs**: Test simple command (`echo hello`), command with stderr, exit code handling,
       timeout, working directory
    6. **grep.rs**: Test pattern matching, case insensitive, glob filter, context lines, limit
    7. **diff.rs**: Test diff_show (generate diff), diff_apply (apply patch), dry run,
       patch that doesn't apply (error)

    Each test should:
    - Create a temp directory with test fixtures
    - Construct params as serde_json::Value
    - Call execute with a ToolContext pointing at the temp dir
    - Assert the output content and is_error flag

    ## Context
    ```rust
    // All tools follow this pattern:
    async fn execute(&self, call_id: &str, params: serde_json::Value, ctx: ToolContext) -> Result<ToolOutput>

    // ToolContext provides:
    pub struct ToolContext {
        pub cwd: PathBuf,
        pub signal: tokio_util::sync::CancellationToken,
    }
    ```

    ## Files
    - crates/imp-core/src/tools/read.rs (modify — add tests)
    - crates/imp-core/src/tools/write.rs (modify — add tests)
    - crates/imp-core/src/tools/edit.rs (modify — add tests)
    - crates/imp-core/src/tools/multi_edit.rs (modify — add tests)
    - crates/imp-core/src/tools/bash.rs (modify — add tests)
    - crates/imp-core/src/tools/grep.rs (modify — add tests)
    - crates/imp-core/src/tools/diff.rs (modify — add tests)

    ## Don't
    - Don't test find/ls/tree_sitter (those have their own beans)
    - Don't mock the filesystem — use real temp dirs
    - Don't skip error cases — test what happens with bad inputs

- id: '1.7'
  title: "imp-llm provider tests (serialization + SSE parsing)"
  status: open
  priority: 0
  parent: '1'
  produces:
    - provider-tests
  has_verify: true
  verify: "cd /Users/asher/imp && cargo test --lib providers -- --nocapture 2>&1 | grep -q 'test result: ok'"
  description: |
    ## Task
    Write unit tests for the Anthropic and OpenAI providers. Focus on serialization
    (unified types → wire format) and SSE event parsing (wire format → StreamEvents).
    No live API calls — use fixture data.

    ## Steps
    1. **Anthropic tests** (in `providers/anthropic.rs`):
       - Test `build_request`: verify JSON structure matches Anthropic API spec
       - Test `convert_message` for each message type (user, assistant with tool calls, tool result)
       - Test `process_sse_event` state machine with fixture SSE event sequences:
         a. Simple text response
         b. Response with thinking + text
         c. Response with tool call (including incremental JSON accumulation)
         d. Error event
         e. Usage tracking (input tokens from MessageStart, output from MessageDelta)
       - Test cache_control placement (system prompt, last tool, recent turns)

    2. **OpenAI tests** (in `providers/openai.rs`):
       - Test request building (map ThinkingLevel → reasoning_effort)
       - Test SSE event parsing for text, tool calls, errors
       - Test message conversion (especially tool results → user messages if needed)

    3. **Message round-trip tests** (in `message.rs`):
       - Serialize Message to JSON, deserialize back, verify equality
       - Test cross-provider context: Anthropic thinking traces → tagged text for OpenAI

    ## Files
    - crates/imp-llm/src/providers/anthropic.rs (modify — add tests module)
    - crates/imp-llm/src/providers/openai.rs (modify — add tests module)
    - crates/imp-llm/src/message.rs (modify — add round-trip tests)

    ## Don't
    - Don't make live API calls — use canned SSE event sequences
    - Don't test Google provider here (it has its own bean)

- id: '1.8'
  title: "Agent loop integration tests"
  status: open
  priority: 1
  parent: '1'
  dependencies:
    - '1.6'
    - '1.7'
  produces:
    - agent-tests
  has_verify: true
  verify: "cd /Users/asher/imp && cargo test --lib agent -- --nocapture 2>&1 | grep -q 'test result: ok'"
  description: |
    ## Task
    Write integration tests for the agent loop using a mock provider that returns
    canned responses with tool calls, verifying the full ReAct cycle.

    ## Steps
    1. Create a `MockProvider` in the test module of `agent.rs`:
       ```rust
       struct MockProvider {
           responses: VecDeque<Vec<StreamEvent>>,
       }
       ```
       Each call to `stream()` pops the next response sequence.

    2. Write test scenarios:
       a. **Simple text response**: Provider returns text, agent emits events, loop ends
       b. **Single tool call**: Provider returns tool_call → tool executes → tool result sent →
          provider returns text → loop ends. Verify tool result is in messages.
       c. **Multi-turn tool calls**: Provider returns tool calls for 3 turns, then text.
          Verify all tool results accumulated.
       d. **Cancel mid-stream**: Send AgentCommand::Cancel during streaming,
          verify partial message saved, loop exits
       e. **Steer mid-loop**: Send AgentCommand::Steer between turns,
          verify steering message injected into context
       f. **Max turns exceeded**: Set max_turns=2, have provider always return tool calls,
          verify Error::MaxTurns returned
       g. **Stream error**: Provider returns StreamEvent::Error,
          verify agent emits error event and returns error

    3. Each test should:
       - Create an Agent with MockProvider + real tools (at minimum read/write)
       - Use a temp directory as cwd
       - Spawn agent.run() and collect events from AgentHandle
       - Assert event sequence and final message state

    ## Files
    - crates/imp-core/src/agent.rs (modify — add tests module with MockProvider)

    ## Don't
    - Don't use real LLM providers
    - Don't test tool execution correctness (that's covered by tool tests)
    - Focus on the loop orchestration: event emission, tool call → result flow, cancellation

- id: '1.9'
  title: "Session manager tests"
  status: open
  priority: 1
  parent: '1'
  produces:
    - session-tests
  has_verify: true
  verify: "cd /Users/asher/imp && cargo test --lib session -- --nocapture 2>&1 | grep -q 'test result: ok'"
  description: |
    ## Task
    Write unit tests for the session manager: JSONL persistence, tree branching, navigation.

    ## Steps
    1. Open `crates/imp-core/src/session.rs`, add `#[cfg(test)] mod tests`
    2. Test scenarios:
       a. **Create + append**: New session, append messages, verify file written as JSONL
       b. **Open + read**: Write a JSONL file manually, open it, verify entries parsed correctly
       c. **Round-trip**: Create session, append various entry types, close, reopen, verify identical
       d. **Branching**: Append entries A→B→C, navigate to B, append D. Verify:
          - get_branch() from D returns A→B→D
          - get_branch() from C returns A→B→C
          - get_tree() shows the fork
       e. **get_messages**: Verify only Message entries returned (not compaction/custom)
       f. **In-memory mode**: Create in_memory(), append entries, verify no file written
       g. **continue_recent**: Create multiple sessions for same cwd, verify most recent returned
       h. **Fork**: Fork from entry B into new session file, verify new file has A→B

    ## Files
    - crates/imp-core/src/session.rs (modify — add tests module)

    ## Don't
    - Don't test session interactions with the agent loop (that's integration testing)
    - Use temp directories for all file operations

# ============================================================================
# PHASE 5: System prompt + context engineering (pi's core insight)
# ============================================================================

- id: '1.10'
  title: "System prompt token budget and measurement"
  status: open
  priority: 0
  parent: '1'
  dependencies:
    - '1.6'
  produces:
    - prompt-budget
  has_verify: true
  verify: "cd /Users/asher/imp && cargo test --lib system_prompt::tests -- --nocapture 2>&1 | grep -q 'test result: ok'"
  description: |
    ## Task
    Add tests that measure and enforce the system prompt token budget.
    Pi's lesson: system prompt + tool definitions should be < 1K tokens baseline.

    ## Steps
    1. Open `crates/imp-core/src/system_prompt.rs`
    2. Add a test that:
       a. Assembles the default system prompt (identity layer + tool descriptions for the core 4 tools)
       b. Counts tokens using the estimate_tokens function from context.rs
       c. Asserts the total is < 1000 tokens
    3. Add a test that:
       a. Assembles the full system prompt with ALL tools enabled
       b. Measures the token count
       c. Asserts it's < 2000 tokens (reasonable budget even with code intelligence tools)
    4. Add a test for each system prompt layer:
       - Layer 1 (identity + tools): measure separately
       - Layer 3 (skills index): measure with sample skills
       - Verify layers concatenate correctly

    ## Context
    ```rust
    // from context.rs
    pub fn estimate_tokens(text: &str) -> u32 {
        (text.len() as u32) / 4
    }
    ```
    Pi achieves < 1K tokens total for system prompt + tool definitions.

    ## Files
    - crates/imp-core/src/system_prompt.rs (modify — add tests)
    - crates/imp-core/src/context.rs (read — estimate_tokens)
    - crates/imp-core/src/tools/mod.rs (read — tool definitions)

    ## Don't
    - Don't change the token estimator to be exact (4 chars/token is good enough for budget checks)
    - Don't add AGENTS.md content to baseline measurement — that's user-controlled

# ============================================================================
# PHASE 6: CLI modes (for orchestration — needed for mana/headless use)
# ============================================================================

- id: '1.11'
  title: "CLI headless mode (imp run)"
  status: open
  priority: 2
  parent: '1'
  dependencies:
    - '1.8'
  produces:
    - headless-mode
  has_verify: true
  verify: "cd /Users/asher/imp && cargo build && ! grep -q 'not yet implemented' crates/imp-cli/src/main.rs"
  description: |
    ## Task
    Implement headless mode: `imp run <unit-id>` reads a task from mana,
    runs the agent, outputs JSON-lines events to stdout, runs verify, exits.

    ## Steps
    1. Open `crates/imp-cli/src/main.rs`
    2. In the `Run` subcommand handler:
       a. Read the mana unit file (from `.beans/` or `.mana/` — check what format imp uses)
       b. Extract: title, description, verify command, notes from previous attempts
       c. Assemble a task prompt from the unit context
       d. Create an Agent with no TUI (NullInterface)
       e. Run the agent loop with the task prompt
       f. Stream AgentEvents as JSON lines to stdout
       g. After agent completes, run the verify command if present
       h. Exit with 0 if verify passes, 1 if not
    3. Handle the case where unit-id doesn't exist (error message, exit 1)

    ## Context
    The blog post emphasizes that headless mode should emit structured events
    so orchestrators can track progress. The existing AgentEvent enum already
    has all the event types needed.

    ## Files
    - crates/imp-cli/src/main.rs (modify — implement Run handler)
    - crates/imp-core/src/agent.rs (read — Agent, AgentEvent types)

    ## Don't
    - Don't implement mana integration as a library dependency yet — just read YAML files directly
    - Don't add interactive prompts in headless mode

- id: '1.12'
  title: "CLI RPC mode (JSON-lines stdin/stdout)"
  status: open
  priority: 2
  parent: '1'
  dependencies:
    - '1.8'
  produces:
    - rpc-mode
  has_verify: true
  verify: "cd /Users/asher/imp && cargo build && ! grep -q 'not yet implemented' crates/imp-cli/src/main.rs"
  description: |
    ## Task
    Implement RPC mode: `imp --mode rpc` speaks JSON-lines over stdin/stdout.
    Client sends commands, receives events. For building custom UIs and integrations.

    ## Steps
    1. Open `crates/imp-cli/src/main.rs`
    2. In the RPC mode handler:
       a. Create an Agent (no TUI)
       b. Spawn two tasks:
          - **Reader**: Read JSON lines from stdin, parse as AgentCommand variants
          - **Writer**: Receive AgentEvents from the agent handle, serialize as JSON lines to stdout
       c. Support commands: `{"type":"prompt","content":"..."}`, `{"type":"cancel"}`,
          `{"type":"steer","content":"..."}`, `{"type":"followup","content":"..."}`
       d. Support events: serialize each AgentEvent variant as JSON with a `type` field
       e. Handle UI requests (from ask tool): emit `{"type":"ui_request",...}` on stdout,
          wait for `{"type":"ui_response",...}` on stdin
       f. Clean shutdown when stdin closes or cancel received

    ## Context
    This is how pi works in headless mode too — structured JSON protocol.
    The StdioInterface from imp_core/ui.rs is designed for this.

    ## Files
    - crates/imp-cli/src/main.rs (modify — implement RPC handler)
    - crates/imp-core/src/ui.rs (read — UserInterface trait, StdioInterface if exists)
    - crates/imp-core/src/agent.rs (read — AgentEvent, AgentCommand)

    ## Don't
    - Don't add authentication to the RPC protocol
    - Don't add WebSocket support — stdin/stdout only

# ============================================================================
# PHASE 7: Performance (pi's key insight: concurrent reads)
# ============================================================================

- id: '1.13'
  title: "Concurrent read-only tool execution"
  status: open
  priority: 1
  parent: '1'
  dependencies:
    - '1.6'
  produces:
    - concurrent-tools
  has_verify: true
  verify: "cd /Users/asher/imp && cargo test --lib agent::tests::test_concurrent -- --nocapture 2>&1 | grep -q 'test result: ok'"
  description: |
    ## Task
    Execute read-only tools concurrently instead of sequentially.
    Currently agent.rs has a comment: "Read-only tools run sequentially for now (concurrent TODO)".

    ## Steps
    1. Open `crates/imp-core/src/agent.rs`, find the `execute_tools` method
    2. Partition tool calls into readonly vs mutable (using `tool.is_readonly()`)
    3. Run readonly tools concurrently using `futures::stream::FuturesUnordered` or similar
    4. Run mutable tools sequentially, in order, after all readonly tools complete
    5. Preserve the original order of results (match tool_call_id order)
    6. Add a test:
       - Create 3 read-only tool calls (e.g., 3 file reads)
       - Verify they all execute and results come back in order
       - Time the execution to verify concurrency (optional)

    ## Context
    The plan specifies this behavior:
    > Read-only tools (read, grep, find, ls, probe_search, probe_extract, scan) — execute concurrently
    > Write tools (write, edit, multi_edit, bash) — execute sequentially, in order
    > Mixed batches: read-only tools run concurrently first, then writes sequentially

    ## Files
    - crates/imp-core/src/agent.rs (modify — execute_tools method)
    - crates/imp-core/src/tools/mod.rs (read — is_readonly() on Tool trait)

    ## Don't
    - Don't change tool execution order for mutable tools
    - Don't add parallelism limits yet (the number of concurrent tool calls is bounded by what the LLM returns)

# ============================================================================
# PHASE 8: Lua tool bridge (connects imp-lua to tool system)
# ============================================================================

- id: '1.14'
  title: "Lua tool bridge"
  status: open
  priority: 2
  parent: '1'
  dependencies:
    - '1.3'
  produces:
    - lua-tool-bridge
  has_verify: true
  verify: "cd /Users/asher/imp && cargo test --lib tools::lua -- --nocapture 2>&1 | grep -q 'test result: ok' && ! grep -q 'TODO' crates/imp-core/src/tools/lua.rs"
  description: |
    ## Task
    Connect the imp-lua extension runtime to the tool registry, so Lua extensions
    can register custom tools via `imp.register_tool()`.

    ## Steps
    1. Open `crates/imp-core/src/tools/lua.rs`
    2. Create a `LuaTool` struct that implements the `Tool` trait:
       - Stores: name, label, description, parameters schema, readonly flag, and a reference
         to the Lua function to call
       - `execute` bridges to the Lua function, converting params to Lua table and result back
    3. Implement `load_lua_tools(lua_runtime, registry)`:
       - Query the Lua runtime for registered tools
       - Create LuaTool instances and register them
    4. In `crates/imp-lua/src/bridge.rs`, verify `imp.register_tool()` stores the tool definition
       so it can be queried by the Rust side
    5. Add a test:
       - Create a Lua runtime with a simple tool registered
       - Load it into a ToolRegistry
       - Execute the tool, verify it calls the Lua function

    ## Files
    - crates/imp-core/src/tools/lua.rs (modify — full implementation)
    - crates/imp-lua/src/bridge.rs (read/modify — ensure register_tool stores definitions)
    - crates/imp-lua/src/lib.rs (read — LuaRuntime API)
    - crates/imp-core/src/tools/mod.rs (read — Tool trait)

    ## Don't
    - Don't change the Lua API surface (imp.register_tool format is already defined)
    - Don't add async Lua execution yet — keep it simple with sync bridge
